It was a little tricky especially with the background as I wanted to make sure that I had none of the pastlemat colour showing through. To achieve this I used the soft pastels and added many layers. The problem being that hard pastels don't layer too easily over soft pastels, soft pastels will easily cover hard pastel though so I had to be careful which layers I was applying and when.

videos.title: Horse at Sunset - Time Lapsed Pastel Portrait - Speed Painting
videos.description:
Horse At Sunset - Time Lapsed Pastel Portrait - Speed Painting
In this video you'll see this beautiful horses portrait come to life! Starting with the blank Pastelmat page all the way to the finished and signed portrait at the end.. and in a fraction of the time!!

This was such a beautiful image to work from, so many fantastic colours to work with to capture the sunset and the last rays of golden sunlight catching on the side of the horses head. I kept the background as close to the original image as possible as it was already out of focus and paid close attention to the balls of light that are breaking through the trees in the far distance. To help keep the portrait as close to the original image, I paid a lot of attention to the reflected light on the horses coat using blues, pinks, greys and purples to get the effect that I was after.

Feel free to ask any questions relating to this video in the comments below, I'll be happy to answer! Thanks for watching!!
 
Materials Used:  Jackson's Art soft pastels, Faber Castell hard pastel sticks and Caran d'Ache pastel pencils on PastelMat card.

videos.title: Greyhound - Time Lapsed Pastel Portrait - Speed Painting
videos.description:
Greyhound - Time Lapsed Pastel Portrait - Speed Painting
In this speed painting video, you will see the Greyhound portrait come to life. Starting from the blank Pastelmat page all the way to the signed and finished portrait at the end.. and in a fraction of the time!

This was a fairly straight forward portrait of a Greyhound with only a few minor changes made from the original image that I felt would help the overall look of the finished portrait. The changes were all in the background, if you look closely at the thumbnail for this time lapsed video, you can see that I've removed the water jug from the original image. I just felt that it would create an unnecessary distraction and by removing it, it would help tidy up the portrait allowing for all focus to be on the dog. The second thing was that I kept the detail work of the fencing to a minimum to again draw attention to the Greyhound.
I paid close attention to something that you possibly hadn't even notice in the video, which is water droplets! Judging by the big tongue, I think that the Greyhound has been for its walk.. probably run.. and just had a refreshing drink as there is a large water droplet towards the end of its tongue and tiny sparkling droplets in the hairs on its muzzle. As I say, you probably didn't notice them (don't worry, I'm not upset!) but it's the small details in a portrait, like the water droplets, that help to tell the story of the happy greyhound, back from its walkies and enjoying a refreshing drink.

Feel free to ask any questions relating to this video in the comments below, I'm happy to answer! Thanks for watching!!

Materials Used: Faber Castell hard pastels and Caran d'Ache pastel pencils on 24x30cm PastelMat card.

videos.title: Amanda - Horse With Blue A Eye - Speed Painting
videos.description:
Amanda - Horse With A Blue Eye - Speed Painting
Watch this pastel portrait of a horse with a blue eye come to life! Starting with the blank Pastelmat page all the way to the signed and finished portrait at the end.. and in a fraction of the time!!

This portrait of was a little tricky, sadly Amanda is no longer with us, so the image that I had to work from was a photograph taken around 20 years ago. To get the image to something that I could work with involved photographing the photo and spending time adjusting the focus, lighting and colour etc. until I had three separate images, each giving different levels of detail, so that I could switch between them taking the best bits from each to create the portrait.

Feel free to ask any questions relating to this video in the comments below, I'll happily answer! Thanks for watching!!

Materials Used: Faber Castell hard pastels, Caran d'Ache pastel pencils and Jackson's art soft pastels on 30x40cm Clairfontaine PastelMat card.

videos.title: Dog In Bluebells - Time Lapsed Pastel Portrait - Speed Painting
videos.description:
Dog In Bluebells - Time Lapsed Pastel Portrait - Speed Painting
In this time lapsed pastel portrait video of this doggy enjoying his walk in the bluebells, you'll see the portrait come together in a fraction of the time. Starting with the blank pastelmat page all the way to the finished and signed portrait at the the end!!

I didn't want to get carried away with adding too much detail to all the long grass around the dog as doing so is not only time consuming but completely unnecessary, it can actually take away from the overall appeal of the finished portrait. Instead of doing this, I kept the detail of the grass and bluebells loose to draw the viewers eye to the dog (the star of the portrait!) and by keeping all of the detail work on the dog, it creates a type of optical illusion in that the portrait appears to have a sense of depth and has been given an almost 3D type quality. The other thing that I was aware of, was that there were very few bluebells on the left side of the image that I was working from, so I simply added in some extra bluebells in the places where I felt that they would help to balance the out the portrait, making it easier on the eye for the viewer.

Your welcome to ask any questions relating to this speed painting video in the comments, I'll be happy to answer! Thanks for watching!

Materials Used: Jackson's soft pastels, Faber Castell hard pastels and Caran d'Ache pastel pencils on 24x30cm PastelMat.

Anyway, by salvaging as much of the art lesson as possible, this spooky Halloween Special - Art Lesson For Kids And Beginners is now finally ready for sharing! So, would you like to know how to begin learning how to use pastels? Or, to create your very own simple but effective zombie hand picture? Or, maybe you'd prefer to see if you can spot anything spooky that may have caused all the technical difficulties? If so, you're braver than I am.. I hope you enjoy it, thanks for watching! Stay safe!!

In this video, I'll show you how to easily draw and make a Snowman Christmas Decoration for your Christmas Tree or home.. or maybe as an amazing gift for someone?
So, drop the iPad (not literally!) grab the glue, have a rifle through the recycling and have a go at some arts and crafts this Christmas!

Things you'll need to make the Snowman Decoration:

*Cardboard
*A pipe cleaner
*A bit of tape
*Glue (PVA or stick glue.. whichever dries fastest!!)
*Cotton wool
*Tinsel or gift ribbon
*Black Sharpie (or similar)
*A bit of string (preferably bauble string)

A nice finishing touch for your mini Christmas Tree, might be some wrapped sweets underneath, positioned to look like small presents?

Things you'll need:

30cm Pipe Cleaners (You choose which colours you want your tree to be!)
Wire cutters (the small kind are fine.. bolt cutters are not necessary!)
*Please be aware that cut pipe cleaners can be sharp, so take care to follow instructions in the video on how to make safe and less pointy!

videos.title: Sculpting a Star Wars creature - Hammerhead - First sculpt
videos.description:
In this video, I'm trying out sculpting for the first time! How hard can it be??

I decided to get a bit creative in this crafty crafts video and actually make something! I'm starting with a movie character or movie alien, I don't think he'd be classed as a monster because.. well, he didn't do anything! He just sits in the Cantina bar at Mos Eisley's space port.. he's not drinking.. I don't think he has a mouth? He could be wondering how he's going to eat his sandwiches? His name is MOMAW NADON aka Hammerhead, from the 1977 movie Star Wars. 
If you follow my channel, you'll notice that I don't post any sculpting videos, that's because I've never sculpted before.. but I do post 'how to' videos and this is a bit of a 'How To' video.. or a 'How Not To' video.. you can decide!?

Lots of fun! Give it a go yourself, if you're interested!!

What you'll need:
Wood, Wire, Foil, Polymer Clay (I used Sculpey), clay sculpting tools (although, I didn't really use mine much.. you could probably just use things from around the home), an oven, a little masking tape and finally acrylic paints. Oh, and you'll need some where that's easy to clean or put some paper down. That's sounds like a lot looking at the list but if you're interested in sculpting and want to create more things, then a lot of this will last you a while!
